`crates/ctx-cage/src/` is the whole `ctx-cage` crate: a `bwrap`-based sandbox that bounds an agent run's blast radius on filesystem, namespaces, and network, plus the host-side plumbing (proxy, broker, runtime staging) that lets a caged process still authenticate and do controlled work. The crate's real entry point is `lifecycle::execute(&Resolved) -> Result<i32, CageError>` (see `lifecycle/rollup.ctx`); everything else here either builds the `Resolved` config fed into it, implements a phase it calls, or is a standalone host-side service it wires up. `CageError` (`error.rs`) is the one error currency threaded through all of it — `Io`/`Json` only via `#[from]`, everything else via `Protocol` with a message.

`cli.rs` resolves CLI flags into a `lifecycle::Mode` and enforces `--allow-spend`/`CTX_CAGE_ALLOW_SPEND` before any billed mode can be constructed; `lifecycle::prepare` and the run phase each re-check `mode_is_billed` independently against that same `Mode`, so a change to which modes count as billed must be verified in three places, not one. Billed mode also pulls in `runtime.rs`, which resolves the host `claude` binary and synthesizes a scoped `~/.claude.json` for staging into the rundir — its `CAGE_BASE_URL` constant assumes the proxy below is what actually gets started.

Two independent egress/access models coexist and must not be conflated: `proxy.rs` is the host-side API-relay used by `lifecycle::run` (OAuth/API-key passthrough, one Unix socket, `SocatUpstream` TLS), while `broker.rs` + `protocol.rs` + `spawn.rs` form a second, allowlisted tool-broker model used by `lifecycle::serve` — its wire format in `protocol.rs` is the same one `bin/ctx_cage_client.rs` speaks from inside the cage, so changing frame layout on one side breaks the other. `spawn.rs`'s `Spawner` trait is the seam `broker.rs` calls through; only `StdSpawner` runs real subprocesses today. `bwrap/` turns whatever `lifecycle`/`runtime` decide on into the actual `bwrap` argv and owns the in-cage path constants (`CAGE_BIN`, `CAGE_RULES_PATH`, etc.) that `runtime.rs` and `lifecycle` must reference rather than hardcode.

`lib.rs` contributes only module wiring and `CAGE_RULES_MD` (agent doctrine embedded via `include_str!`), which whatever constructs the real `claude` launch (`cli`/`lifecycle`) must keep passing via `--append-system-prompt-file`. `summarize.rs` is unrelated to sandbox execution proper — it's post-run `.ctx` leaf regeneration invoked by `bin/ctx_run.rs` after a task finishes, not part of the cage lifecycle itself. `bin/` holds the three process entry points (`ctx-cage`, `ctx-run`, `ctx-cage-client`) that assemble these pieces into host and in-cage executables.